In this test you reassign `provider` to a new `AdoWorkItemProvider` without disposing the instance created in `beforeEach`. That can leak listeners/timers across tests and make timer-based tests flaky if the old instance had scheduled refresh. Dispose the existing provider before reassigning (or create a separate local variable for this test).
```suggestion
  it('uses org-level WIQL when no projects are configured', async () => {
    provider.dispose();
```

`organization`/`projects` are read once during activation and then baked into provider instances. That means changing `workcenterAdo.organization` or `workcenterAdo.projects` in settings wonΓÇÖt take effect until the user reloads the window. Consider either reading configuration inside each `refresh()` or wiring `onDidChangeConfiguration` to recreate/reconfigure providers when these settings change.
```suggestion
  let workItemProvider: AdoWorkItemProvider | undefined;
  let prProvider: AdoPrReviewProvider | undefined;
  let workItemRegistration: vscode.Disposable | undefined;
  let prRegistration: vscode.Disposable | undefined;

  const configureProviders = () => {
    // Dispose existing providers and registrations before reconfiguring
    if (workItemRegistration) {
      workItemRegistration.dispose();
      workItemRegistration = undefined;
    }
    if (prRegistration) {
      prRegistration.dispose();
      prRegistration = undefined;
    }
    if (workItemProvider) {
      workItemProvider.dispose();
      workItemProvider = undefined;
    }
    if (prProvider) {
      prProvider.dispose();
      prProvider = undefined;
    }

    const config = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration('workcenterAdo');
    const org = config.get<string>('organization', '');
    const projects = config.get<string[]>('projects', []);

    if (!org) {
      // No organization configured; leave providers unregistered.
      return;
    }

    const intervalSeconds = config.get<number>('refreshIntervalSeconds', 300);

    workItemProvider = new AdoWorkItemProvider(org, projects);
    prProvider = new AdoPrReviewProvider(org, projects);

    workItemProvider.startPeriodicRefresh(intervalSeconds);
    prProvider.startPeriodicRefresh(intervalSeconds);

    workItemRegistration = api.registerProvider(workItemProvider);
    prRegistration = api.registerProvider(prProvider);
  };

  // Initial configuration based on current settings
  configureProviders();

  const configChangeSubscription = vscode.workspace.onDidChangeConfiguration(e => {
    if (
      e.affectsConfiguration('workcenterAdo.organization') ||
      e.affectsConfiguration('workcenterAdo.projects') ||
      e.affectsConfiguration('workcenterAdo.refreshIntervalSeconds')
    ) {
      configureProviders();
    }
  });

  const cleanupDisposable: vscode.Disposable = {
    dispose: () => {
      if (workItemRegistration) {
        workItemRegistration.dispose();
        workItemRegistration = undefined;
      }
      if (prRegistration) {
        prRegistration.dispose();
        prRegistration = undefined;
      }
      if (workItemProvider) {
        workItemProvider.dispose();
        workItemProvider = undefined;
      }
      if (prProvider) {
        prProvider.dispose();
        prProvider = undefined;
      }
    },
  };

  _context.subscriptions.push(
    configChangeSubscription,
    cleanupDisposable,
```

The local `WorkCenterProvider` interface is meant to mirror the core extension contract, but itΓÇÖs missing the optional `resurfaceDismissed?: boolean` property (present in core `WorkCenterProvider`). Keeping these redeclared types in sync avoids confusion and makes it easier to copy patterns between providers; add the optional property here for parity.
```suggestion
  readonly label: string;
  readonly resurfaceDismissed?: boolean;
```

When `Promise.allSettled` returns a `rejected` result, the failure is recorded but the underlying error (`result.reason`) is dropped, which makes diagnosing network/JSON failures hard. Consider logging the rejection reason in the `else` branch (and/or including it in the warning) so failures arenΓÇÖt silent in logs.
```suggestion
        const failureTarget = projectList[index] || this.org;
        failures.push(failureTarget);
        const reason = (result as PromiseRejectedResult).reason;
        logger.warn(
          `Failed to fetch work items from ${failureTarget}: ` +
          (reason instanceof Error ? reason.message : String(reason)),
        );
```

As with the work item provider, `Promise.allSettled` rejections are treated as failures but the rejection reason is discarded. Logging `result.reason` (at least at error/debug level) in the rejected branch would make it much easier to troubleshoot intermittent fetch/parse issues.
```suggestion
        const target = projectList[index] || this.org;
        failures.push(target);
        logger.error(
          `Failed to fetch PR reviews from ${target}: ${String(
            (result as PromiseRejectedResult).reason,
          )}`,
        );
```
